Quesh: What is something that you've learned to accept?
Respo: That I am here and not there. That sounds really obtuse aloud! The story is I have this tendency to daydream that self-love and self-realization would be easier had I not ended up back in my hometown. But I chose to come back here. I am here. Not there. And Ive had to learn to accept that fact so I can start to learn to love & be proud of who I am here right now, and by extension, learn to heal & forgive & even maybe be proud of parts of who I used to be when I was here back then.

Quesh: What was the best hotel experience you've had?
Respo: The Breakers in Palm Beach! I was an intern working a convention there and I fell in love? The whole hotel trip was the best Ive ever had and I hope to be able to go back at some point for a non-work trip! Storytime: since I was working so much, I ordered room service a lot and the staff was so lovely and the food delicious. On my last night, I left them a thank you note on the door and the following day they sent me my regular breakfast order up for free as a thank you. *this is a friendly reminder to thank hotel staff as they do a lot for little recognition. The room service team told me that not many people thank them and my note made them so happy. Now when I experience excellent service, I make a point to say thank you or tell management so the person/team can get recognized!

Quesh: In your dream world, what issue(s) would be resolved?
Respo: Oh man, that list is undeniably long. Though as much as Id love for world peace to truly be present in this moment and from this moment on, it does not seem physically possible. Not everyone in this world seeks peace, because they do not have peace within themselves. Some feel it is impossible to achieve it; whether it be in their own minds or their relationships with other beings. & whats with that saying, peace is worth fighting for, fighting can be a physical term or a spiritual term. Physically, definitely defeats the purpose of peace. & spiritually, we are all fighting our ego to find our way back home to our purest selves. So, my dream world issue to be resolved would be for everyone to find peace within themselves thus allowing them to find peace within others. ?

Quesh: What have you learned about love?
Respo: Its different for everyone. Like the way people express it is very different and not everyone is the same so you cant expect someone o treat you the way another did.

Quesh: What have you learned about love?
Respo: Im not sure this answers the questionbut something Ive learned and seen in other relationships is dont lose yourself for the other person. Dont change your hobbies, dreams, interests if they dont match up. Its okay to like different things. I think love is when two individual people come together and learn from each other and share experiences together while knowing you both are independent but are making the choice to come together and share life together. An example, Im not a runner so if I ever dated a runner, Im not going to change myself and start running to make the other feel better. Ill continue doing what I enjoy (yoga) and support them in their hobby/passion from the sideline. We can still support and lift each other up without changing who we are.
Respo Comment: Very thought provoking. I had to really sit back and think on this oneâ¤ï¸

Love is inspirational & driving.. so try to have it steer you in the right direction. I love music, my friends, my family, my wife, my son.. all so differently. I read a book by Common titled Let Love Have The Last Word. It talks about letting Love drive our actions, our motives, our thoughts. Id recommend it to any readers out there.

Quesh: What has been the biggest surprise of 2021?
Respo: For me, it was being recruited to work for another company and actually feeling recognized & appreciated. Ive always been the type to keep my mouth shut & just work hard every day, believing that youll get what you put in. But I was used to that effort kinda going unrecognized at my last company. My new employer sought me out & made me an offer I really couldnt believe (or refuse). Now I make more, work less hours, have a shorter commute, and truly get a lot of respect in the work place.. to be honest, it was pretty shocking & hard to believe / get used to at first. It has been a big surprise & a big change. But man.. it sure has been validating! To all you out there working hard, keep going!

Quesh: What is something you want that money can't buy?
Respo: Peace of mind. Im anxious. I doubt my abilities. I worry Im not skilled enough, not smart enough & that I dont work hard enough. Im not fun enough yet Im not responsible enough. I dont make enough money. Im not cut out to be a father figure or role model or husband. Over the years, I think Ive learned how to monitor these thoughts & make conscious efforts to correct them. But theyre always there. Sometimes I think I can use these thoughts to motivate me to push harder.. but it would be nice to not always have that edginess about myself. I counter these thoughts by just trying to be grateful. I have so much love in my life - and recognizing that is so reassuring. Knowing youre loved & you are enough and dammit youre doing great that feeling is priceless

Respo: 6.5? Totally depends on what Im shopping for. Sometimes retail therapy is a very real thing, sometimes I love researching a product & when I buy it I feel good about making a great decision, and sometimes Im just looking forward to taking a purchase home. But other times shopping gives me anxiety. Its usually due to external factors though such as wondering where Im going to put something, doubting if its something I really need, or if its worth it. My wife did surprise me with an epic Year 27 belated-birthday trip to Chicago though .. that maybe doesnt count but I have to mention. Surprise trip to Tesla, where I test drove a Model S, to Lagunitas (my favorite brewery) to Shedds Aquarium, where I got to PET A PENGUIN, and then went to dinner at the restaurant we got engaged at. Quesh: Who has been your best teacher and why?
Respo: There are so many teachers in my life but the best have been my father and mother. When the conversation wasnt about my day or school or work, I would learn something new from my dad about nature, art, God, myself, or a random diy house project. He taught me that I can do almost anything if Im willing to be creative and to take action. Because my parents are a package deal I must include my mom. She taught me that Im never alone, that I am worthy of love, and that there is always something you can offer to another. She taught me to be like butter, dont let things stick to you can let them slide right off of you. Shes also taught me how to live a life like Jesus by being like him and by loving so gracefully. I have two of the best teachers and they love me and each other, how lucky.
Respo Comment: I think it was a great question, it made me grateful and pensive

Quesh: Who has been your best teacher and why?
Respo: I had a prof in college who had a reputation for being tough. People avoided his classes - but there was a string of classmates who swore by him. I took two of his courses in the same semester & decided to totally buy whatever he was selling. He probably did his homework on me & knew I didnt have the GPA of his other students because he challenged me individually - but was always coming from a sense of You can do this. He had high expectations, but his lessons forced me to change as a student - I became more accountable, took better notes, asked questions. This forced me to be more engaged & I learned more from his class than any other of my coursework. I challenged myself by taking the course, but he met my challenge by pushing me. He wanted me to succeed & made me believe I could

Quesh: Who has been your best teacher and why?
Respo: My 3rd grade teacher, Shiela McCauley. I absolutely loved her. Funny, I prayed all summer going into 4th grade that I could have her as my teacher again. First day of 4th grade I walked into the class room and sure enough, I had her for 4th grade too. She just left such a positive impact, loved her students and was patient and kind. That was 1977/78. In 2014 I got to reconnect with her, have lunch and visit the old elementary school and the classrooms where she taught us. We now stay in touch through social media.

Quesh: Who has been your best teacher and why?
Respo: School-wise, my best teacher was my 9th grade geometry teacher. The irony is that I struggled SO much in that class but she became a mentor and confidant, and now she is my friend! We talk nearly everyday, nearly 15 years later. :)
